definitions.definition: Passing from one side of something to the other.
examples: Interstate highways form a nationwide system of through roads.
They were through with laying the subroof by noon.

definitions.definition: Along the course of a task etc.; used in expressions of progress towards the end .
examples: It's a big job but we're halfway through .
After being implicated in the scandal, he was through as an executive in financial services.

definitions.definition: No longer interested; wearied or turned off by experience.
Proceeding from origin to destination without the need to change transport vehicle.
examples: The through flight through Memphis was the fastest.
When is the next through train to London?

definitions.definition: In possession of the ball beyond the last line of defence but not necessarily the goalkeeper ; through on goal .
Able to progress (to the next stage or a higher level) following success in an exam, sports match, etc.
examples: Manchester United are through to the FA Cup Final for the thirteenth time.
label_groups: chiefly UK , Commonwealth , Ireland , rare in Canada
